<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-766-780  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 766 780.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  August 24 1989 v37 n18 p37(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Options expand for broadband networking; analog broadbandtechnology may compete with evolving digital techniques.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leonard, Milt.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Broadband networking technology is expected to have a brightfuture as the basis for interconnection of local area networks(LAN) and scattered computers, though the current coaxial cabletechnology will likely be replaced by emerging fiber optictechnology.andP;  A growing number of vendors are producing theequipment users need to implement coaxial cable-based broadbandnetworks.andP;  Maturing experience in the installation and applicationof the networks will also bring coaxial cable technology intowider acceptance.andP;  Fiber optics offers another approach tobroadband networks that may end up replacing the coaxial approach.andO;Wider vendor support, lower cost of fiber components and theacceptance of the Fiber Distribution Data Interface (FDDI)Standard should make fiber optics more applicable to LAN use.andP;  AnFDDI-based network can take advantage of the tremendous speed ofgallium arsenide communications circuits.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsBroadband networksCoaxial cablesLocal Area NetworksCommunications Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Broadband network. (chart)Single-cable networks. (chart)Fiber-optic links. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>